{{NCAATeamFootballSeason |Year=2008 |Team= New Mexico Lobos |Image= |ImageSize= 120 |Conference= Mountain West Conference |ShortConference= MWC |Record= 4â8 |ConfRecord= 2â6 |HeadCoach= [[Rocky Long]] |OffCoach= |DefCoach= |OScheme= |DScheme= |StadiumArena=[[University Stadium (Albuquerque)|University Stadium]] |Champion= |BowlTourney= |BowlTourneyResult= }} {{2008 Mountain West Conference football standings}} The '''2008 New Mexico Lobos football team''' represented the [[University of New Mexico]] in [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[Division I (NCAA)#Football Bowl Subdivision|Football Bowl Subdivision]] (FBS) [[college football]] during the [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008 season]]. New Mexico competed as a member of the [[Mountain West Conference]] (MWC), and played their home games in the [[University Stadium (Albuquerque)|University Stadium]]. The Lobos were led by 11th-year head coach [[Rocky Long]].
The Lobos upset ten-point favorites [[2008 Arizona Wildcats football team|Arizona]], 36â28.<ref name=steele/> Against ninth-ranked [[2008 BYU Cougars football team|BYU]], New Mexico had a fourth quarter [[touchdown]] overturned due to a controversial penalty call. On fourth [[down (American football)|down]] with 21 yards to go, the Lobos then failed to convert for a first down. BYU scored on their next possession to clinch the victory, 21â3.<ref name=steele>''Phil Steele's 2009 College Football Preview'', vol. 15, p. 190, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=282850252 BYU extends nation's longest winning streak to 16 straight], ESPN, October 11, 2008.</ref> New Mexico also played a close game against 10th-ranked [[2008 Utah Utes football team|Utah]], which finished the season undefeated and ranked second in the nation. The Lobos were stopped at the Utes' goal line on fourth down, and eventually lost by a three-point margin.<ref name=steele/>
New Mexico finished the season with a 4â8 record (MWC: 2â6).<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_game_by_game.php?coachid=1398&year=2008 New Mexico 2008], College Football Data Warehouse, retrieved June 27, 2009.</ref> It was the Lobos' first losing season in conference play since 2000.<ref>Steele, p. 172.</ref> After the season, Rocky Long resigned as head coach. He was replaced by former [[Illinois Fighting Illini football|Illinois]] [[offensive coordinator]], [[Mike Locksley]].<ref>[http://www.cbssports.com/collegefootball/story/11159718 Illini OC Locksley hired as head coach at New Mexico], [[CBS Sports]], December 8, 2008.</ref>
